# Feature Development Workflow

## Purpose
Guide an AI agent through the complete feature development lifecycle: from branch creation to PR merge. This workflow enforces a disciplined process that produces well-tested, reviewable code.

## Steps to Generate

### 1. Create Feature Branch
// capture: BRANCH_NAME
Create a new branch from the latest main/develop branch following the project's naming convention (e.g., `feature/short-description`).
- Pull latest changes from the base branch
- Create and switch to the feature branch
- Push the branch to origin to establish tracking

### 2. Understand the Requirement
Before writing code, ensure the requirement is clear:
- Read the issue/ticket description
- Identify acceptance criteria
- List the files and modules likely to be affected
- Identify edge cases and potential risks

### 3. Plan the Implementation
// if the change touches more than 3 files
Break down the feature into small, incremental steps:
- Define the order of changes (domain → application → infrastructure → interface)
- Identify dependencies between changes
- Plan the test strategy (unit, integration, acceptance)

### 4. Implement with Tests
Write code following the project's architecture and conventions:
- Write tests first when possible (TDD cycle)
- Keep commits atomic and focused (one logical change per commit)
- Follow the project's coding standards and linting rules
- Run tests after each significant change

### 5. Run Full Test Suite
// turbo
Run the complete test suite to catch regressions:
- Unit tests
- Integration tests
- Linting and static analysis

### 6. Self-Review the Diff
Before creating a PR, review your own changes:
- Read the complete diff as if reviewing someone else's code
- Check for: leftover debug code, TODOs, commented-out code, hardcoded values
- Verify commit messages follow the project's convention
- Ensure no sensitive data (keys, passwords) is included

### 7. Create Pull Request
Create a well-structured PR:
- Write a clear title summarizing the change
- Include a description with: what changed, why, and how to test
- Link related issues/tickets
- Add appropriate reviewers and labels

### 8. Address Review Feedback
// if there is review feedback
Process each review comment:
- Acknowledge each comment
- Implement requested changes in new commits (don't amend during review)
- Re-request review after addressing all feedback
- Run tests again after changes

### 9. Merge and Clean Up
// turbo
After approval:
- Merge using the project's preferred strategy (squash, merge, rebase)
- Delete the feature branch
- Verify the merge in the base branch

## Anti-patterns
- Giant PRs with unrelated changes (split them)
- Force-pushing during review (makes it impossible to see incremental changes)
- Skipping tests before PR creation
- Vague commit messages ("fix stuff", "updates")
- Not pulling latest base branch before starting
